{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535824"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:00:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:00:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15526"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15526","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15526"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.04,0.08,0.74,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8217"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61736"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8217","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8217"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15526"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47182"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"16"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5462"},{"type":"tags","id":"9586"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19877"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61736"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic requesting advice about starting a new medication for primary prevention of cardiovascular disease. She has read about a large clinical trial of this medication. The trial randomised 2,000 participants to either treatment or placebo. In the treatment group, 40 of 1,000 participants experienced a cardiovascular event over five years. In the placebo group, 80 of 1,000 participants experienced a cardiovascular event over the same period.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the relative risk reduction for cardiovascular events with this treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["40%","60%","20%","50%","80%"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question tests understanding of relative risk reduction calculation, which is crucial for interpreting clinical trial results and communicating benefits to patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo calculate relative risk reduction, we first need to determine the risk in each group. A two by two table helps organize this data:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cdiv class=\u0022table-container\u0022\u003E\u003Ctable border=\u00221\u0022 style=\u0022border-collapse:collapse;margin:10px;\u0022\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Cth\u003E\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003EEvent\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003ENo Event\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003ETotal\u003C/th\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ETreatment\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E40\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E960\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E1000\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EPlacebo\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E80\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E920\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E1000\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003C/table\u003E\u003C/div\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk in treatment group = 40/1000 = 0.04 or 4%Risk in placebo group = 80/1000 = 0.08 or 8%\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe formula for relative risk reduction is:(Risk in control - Risk in treatment) / Risk in control \u00d7 100%= (0.08 - 0.04) / 0.08 \u00d7 100%= 0.04 / 0.08 \u00d7 100%= 0.5 \u00d7 100%= \u003Cstrong\u003E50%\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E20%\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003E40%\u003C/strong\u003E are incorrect calculations that might result from using the wrong denominator or misunderstanding the concept of relative versus absolute risk reduction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E60%\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003E80%\u003C/strong\u003E are incorrect calculations that might result from using the treatment group risk as the denominator or calculating the percentage reduction in events rather than the relative risk reduction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe absolute risk reduction in this case would be 4% (8% - 4% = 4%), which is different from the relative risk reduction. Relative risk reduction tends to produce larger numbers than absolute risk reduction and is commonly used in reporting trial results, though absolute risk reduction may be more meaningful for individual patient decisions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Relative risk reduction is calculated as (risk in control - risk in treatment) / risk in control x 100%.","Two by two tables help organize data for calculating risk in clinical trials.","Understanding relative risk reduction helps clinicians interpret and communicate treatment benefits."],"references":["Talluri SK. Relative risk reduction and absolute risk reduction. BMJ. 2009 Sep 16;339:b3626."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47182"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15526"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47182"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-16T11:46:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-16T11:49:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8217"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61736"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"16","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/16"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udcca","name":"Biostatistics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"